22:25.177 --> 22:29.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Yang has our look. And a
warning: The
story contains some graphic
images.

22:29.315 --> 22:34.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: There is a calamity
in the making
in Nigeria's northeastern Borno
state. That's

22:34.687 --> 22:39.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the territory where government
forces have
been fighting Boko Haram for
years. Caught

22:39.725 --> 22:46.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the middle, as many as three
million Nigerians,
who, aid groups say, are in
danger of starving.

22:46.365 --> 22:50.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is also where those Chibok
girls were kidnapped
in 2014.

22:50.970 --> 22:55.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Washington Post correspondent
Kevin Sieff
just completed a reporting trip
there, and

22:55.608 --> 22:57.943 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he joins us from Nairobi, Kenya.

22:57.977 --> 23:02.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Kevin, you write this morning in
The Post
about this growing humanitarian
crisis, this

23:02.681 --> 23:05.284 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
famine. How widespread is it?

23:05.317 --> 23:07.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN SIEFF, The Washington
Post: Yes, it's
massive.

23:07.353 --> 23:13.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're talking about a population
of more than
three million, far more,
probably closer to

23:13.859 --> 23:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
four million. Two million of
them are entirely
inaccessible. So, you have got
humanitarian

23:18.731 --> 23:23.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
actors who have just started to
work in this
place of Northern -- this place
called Northern

23:23.102 --> 23:24.870 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Borno state.

23:24.903 --> 23:30.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, even so, there are two
million people
who are basically -- they're in
villages or

23:30.509 --> 23:36.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're in cities where Boko
Haram still operates
with impunity. And so
humanitarian actors

23:36.649 --> 23:39.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can't deliver food, they can't
deliver medicine
to two million people.

23:39.952 --> 23:46.258 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The other basically
million-and-a-half, actors
have just gotten access to them.
And so there

23:46.292 --> 23:49.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are food deliveries, but there's
just not
enough food. There's not enough
medicine.

23:49.962 --> 23:55.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So you're just seeing massive
rates of malnutrition,
dozens of children dying every
day.

23:55.801 --> 23:59.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have talked to aid workers
when I was up
there who said they'd never seen
anything

23:59.305 --> 24:02.975 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
like this. It's just -- it's
huge.

24:03.008 --> 24:08.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: In your story, Kevin,
you write
very movingly about coming upon
a 6-month-old

24:08.147 --> 24:10.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
girl in a clinic. Tell us about
that.

24:10.883 --> 24:12.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KEVIN SIEFF: Yes.

24:12.718 --> 24:19.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The girl's name was Fana Ali.
She was 6 months
old. She looked like she had
just been born.

24:19.291 --> 24:27.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was tiny. She basically had
been malnourished
since birth. And she was in a
clinic run by

24:27.633 --> 24:34.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Doctors Without Borders in a
small city called
Banki right on the Cameroonian
border.

24:34.707 --> 24:42.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And she had malaria and
malnutrition. The
doctors tried really valiantly
to save her

24:42.614 --> 24:46.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this little clinic with no
electricity,
basically no medicine, almost no
resources

24:46.985 --> 24:48.754 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at all.

24:48.787 --> 24:53.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, ultimately, they had to try
to get her
out of there, but the place is
so dangerous,

24:53.459 --> 24:57.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's so hard to leave by road.
They had to
get an escort from the military,
from the

24:57.463 --> 25:03.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cameroonian military. And that
escort basically
just didn't come for reasons
that no one really

25:03.268 --> 25:05.104 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
knows.

25:05.137 --> 25:14.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And just after the escort was
rejected, the
baby girl died. And, you know,
it's a tragedy.

25:14.213 --> 25:19.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And seeing it is horrific for me
and for the
people who were trying to save
her.

25:19.918 --> 25:25.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, ultimately, it's the kind
of thing that
is just happening hourly in
northeastern Nigeria

25:25.991 --> 25:31.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now. It's happening all the
time. There is
just not enough assistance.
There's not enough

25:31.397 --> 25:37.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
food. There are children
starving to death
all -- just all over that
region.

25:37.136 --> 25:42.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what I find so striking and
sad about
it is that this has been going
on for a long

25:42.841 --> 25:47.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time, you know? I mean, these
places were
liberated from Boko Haram about
a year-and-a-half

25:47.079 --> 25:54.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ago. And we have seen children
like Fana Ali
starving and dying since then.
And assistance

25:54.219 --> 25:55.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
still isn't coming.

25:56.021 --> 26:00.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Why is it taking so
long? Why has
it taken so long for this famine
to become

26:00.826 --> 26:02.594 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
known?

26:02.628 --> 26:06.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEVIN SIEFF: I think part of it
is that it's
so dangerous. It's difficult for
aid workers,

26:06.398 --> 26:09.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's different for journalists
to get access
to these places.

26:09.568 --> 26:17.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it took a long time for a
lot of people,
including us, to learn just how
dire things

26:17.242 --> 26:22.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really were. I think that's one
reason. I
think another reason is, there
was just a

26:22.681 --> 26:30.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
total institutional failure both
at the U.N.
and within other international
NGOs that really

26:30.155 --> 26:35.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
should have known how bad things
were, but
simply didn't have the resources
in Nigeria,

26:35.761 --> 26:41.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
didn't have strong enough teams,
weren't trying
hard enough to find out what the
situation

26:41.900 --> 26:46.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really looked like outside of
the capital
of the state.

26:46.038 --> 26:52.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as soon as they did get
access or kind
of tried to leave the capital,
these horrific

26:52.711 --> 26:59.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
images started coming out. So, I
think it's
a combination of those factors,
and those

26:59.117 --> 27:02.688 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
factors continue to plague the
response.

27:02.721 --> 27:08.694 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Even in places that are
relatively safe, like
Maiduguri, the capital of Borno,
you have

27:08.727 --> 27:13.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
got severe acute malnutrition
rates that are
the highest in the world. You
have the return

27:13.565 --> 27:19.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of polio, the first polio cases
in Africa
in about two years.

27:19.404 --> 27:26.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By almost every measure, this is
a crisis
as bad as we have seen anywhere
in sub-Saharan

27:26.411 --> 27:28.180 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Africa in a very long time.

27:28.213 --> 27:31.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Kevin Sieff of The
Washington Post,
thank you very much for your
reporting on

27:31.450 --> 27:35.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this very troubling story.
Thanks for being
with us.

27:35.187 --> 27:42.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
